description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/senml/senml.c
Lines: 308-339, specifically 321-329

CATEGORY: CORRECTNESS / PROTOCOL

senml_encode_location() accepts float lat and lon parameters but doesn't validate them:

  ret = senml_add_float(&pack, 'lat', 'deg', lat);
  ret = senml_add_float(&pack, 'lon', 'deg', lon);

If lat or lon is NaN or Infinity, the function will encode these invalid values. WGS84 coordinates have valid ranges:
  - Latitude: -90.0 to +90.0
  - Longitude: -180.0 to +180.0

Encoding NaN or Inf violates the semantics of geographic coordinates even though CBOR can represent them.

The alt parameter IS validated (line 331):
  if (!isnan(alt)) { ... }

But this only skips NaN altitude, it doesn't reject NaN - the inconsistency suggests lat/lon should also be validated.

IMPACT:
- Invalid location data propagates to receivers
- Receivers may crash or produce undefined behavior
- GPS fix failures (NaN) silently become encoded as 'valid' data

FIX: Add validation:
  if (isnan(lat) || isnan(lon) || isinf(lat) || isinf(lon)) {
      return -EINVAL;
  }
  if (lat < -90.0f || lat > 90.0f || lon < -180.0f || lon > 180.0f) {
      return -ERANGE;
  }
